IST 707 HW1- Association Rule Mining

-Mihir Deshpande

February 10, 2019

This Homework assigments deals with mining interesting rules to predict income. ‘AdultUCI’ dataset from ‘arules’ package in used for the analysis.Steps involved in the process are:-

1.Cleaning the dataset and getting it in the desired format which is suitable for the apiori method.

-Dealing with missing values- A dual approach was used to deal with missing values.Income variable,which is the variable of interest has almost 1/3rd values missing.Imputing this variable may result in non-credible results.Therefore rows with missing values in the income variable were deleted.Rest of the variables with missing values were imputed using K-NN imputation using DMwR package

-Discretization of numeric variable with discrete classes.This is needed as the apriori method does not work with numeric values.Special care was taken to deal with 'captial-gain' and 'capital-loss' variables are they have majority of values as zero

-Qualitative variables with many levels were collapsed into fewer levels. This was done because apriori association rule method does not work well with categorical variable with many levels

  1. Visual Data exploration- Using tidyverse and ggplot2, barplots to analyse income against different variables were plotted. Insights generated were reported.

  2. Association Rule mining using apriori method- The record dataset was converted into a transactional dataset to perform the analysis.Apiori method with default values used first and then experimented with different parameter values to generate top rules. Rules to predict income mined.Visuaisation of the mined rules was done using ‘plot’ function and arulesViz package. 4.Shiny Application to access and visualise top rules based on user given parameters created and deployed on shinyapps.io . Link to the app is provided below.

adultDf<-adultDf[!(is.na(adultDf$income)),]

Dicretization:-

Dicretizing the age variable into low,medium and high :-

adultDf$age_grp <- discretize(adultDf$age, method = "frequency", breaks = 3, 
                               labels = c("low", "medium", "high"), order = T)

Dicretizing the fnl-wgt variable into small,medium and large:-

adultDf$fnlwgt<-discretize(adultDf$fnlwgt,method = "frequency",breaks=3,labels = c("small","medium","large"),order=T)

Discretizing ‘hours-per-week’ variable using “cluster” method of discretize function which uses clustering alogorithm to achieve dicretization.evels used are low,medium,high and very high:-

adultDf$`hours-per-week`<-discretize(adultDf$`hours-per-week`,method = "cluster",breaks=4,labels=c("low","medium","high","very-high"),order=T)
#For Capital gain and capital loss variables, most frequent values are 0.Function used to achieve discretization is cut() and breaks selected accordingly

Discretization for ‘capital-gain’ into levels Zero,Below_10000 and Above_10000:-

adultDf$capital_gain<-cut(adultDf$`capital-gain`,c(-Inf,0,10000,99999),labels = c("Zero","Below_10000","Above_10000"))

Discretization for ‘capital-loss’ into levels Zero,Below_2000 and Above_2000:-

adultDf$capital_loss<-cut(adultDf$`capital-loss`,c(-Inf,0,2000,Inf),labels=c("Zero","Below_2000","Above_2000"))

A function to subset rules and sort them based on decreasing value of lift.This is done to remove redundant rules and get the top rules based on lift:-

subset_rules<-function(Rules){
  sub_rules <- which(colSums(is.subset(Rules,Rules)) > 1)#Removing redundant rules
  Rules <- sort(Rules[-sub_rules], by = "lift", descreasing = T)
  return(Rules)
}

plot(income_large_rules[1:5], method='graph')

Analysis:-

1.A support of 0.02 and confidence of 0.4 is chosen by analysing the scatterplot of rules.Rules in that region had high support,confidence and lift.

2.{Capital_gain=Abobe_10000} seems like a very good rule to predict income and its intuitive as people with high capital again will tend to have higher income.

  1. {workclass=Self Employed,occupation=White Collar} is also an interesting rule as people who with white collar jobs having own businesses have a good chance of being in the large income pool.This rule is consistent with the insight from the barplot.

4.{education=University,age_grp=high} is again an interesting rules as people with a university degree will have higher chance of being in the large income pool and so are people with high age.This rule is consistent with the insight from the barplot.

5.{occupation=White Collar,sex=Male} is also an interesting rule as men are more likely to be in the large income pool due to cultural imbalance and lack of oppurtunity for women. This rule is consistent with the findings from the barplot.

Analysis:-

1.support of 0.15 and confidence of 0.9 chosen by analysing the scatterplot of rules.Rules in that region had high support,confidence and lift.

2.{maritalstatus=Unmarried,age_grp=low,capital_gain=Zero} is an intersting rule as umarried people are less stable in general than married people and tend to have lower incomes.Young people will also have smaller incomes as compared to oler people and zero capital gain indicates no growth. The rule is consistent with the insights derived from the barplot.

3.{relationship=Own Child} is an interesting rule as people with dependents have more responsibilities at home and can be less productive because of that.

  1. Marital status looks like an intersting factor that can determine the income.
